@page
@using DPVreony.Website.Features.Articles
@using NodaTime
@{
    var articleMetadata = new ArticleMetadataModel(
        ArticleStatus.Released,
        new Version(1, 0),
        new LocalDate(2021, 05, 31),
        new LocalDate(2026, 03, 27),
        new LocalDate(2026, 03, 27),
        new LocalDate(2026, 09, 27));
}
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-8">
        <h1>Crawling a website as an integration test.</h1>

        <h2>Introduction</h2>
        <p>
            Integration testing web applications often involves testing individual endpoints or user flows in isolation. 
            However, a comprehensive approach is to crawl your entire website systematically, following all internal links 
            to ensure every page loads successfully without errors. This technique helps identify broken links, missing resources, 
            server errors, and routing issues that might not be caught by unit tests or limited integration tests.
        </p>
        <p>
            By implementing a web crawler as part of your integration test suite, you can automatically verify that all pages 
            in your application are accessible, render correctly, and return appropriate HTTP status codes. This approach is 
            particularly valuable for static site generators, content management systems, and any web application with a 
            significant number of interconnected pages.
        </p>

        <h2>ASP.NET Core Integration Testing with Playwright</h2>
        <p>
            ASP.NET Core provides powerful capabilities for integration testing through the 
            <code>Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing</code> package, which allows you to create an in-memory test server using 
            <code>WebApplicationFactory&lt;TEntryPoint&gt;</code>. When combined with Playwright.NET, you can crawl your entire 
            website without any external HTTP traffic, making it ideal for running on your local development machine or as part 
            of your CI/CD pipeline.
        </p>
        <p>
            The in-memory test server approach offers several advantages: it runs entirely within your test process, doesn't 
            require port binding or network configuration, provides fast test execution, and ensures complete isolation from 
            external dependencies. By integrating Playwright.NET, you gain access to a real browser engine (Chromium, Firefox, 
            or WebKit) that can execute JavaScript, handle client-side routing, and validate the fully rendered output of your 
            web application.
        </p>
        <p>
            A critical aspect of integrating Playwright.NET with <code>WebApplicationFactory</code> is the need to intercept and 
            route page requests through the in-memory test server. Since Playwright operates as a real browser that makes actual 
            HTTP requests, you must use Playwright's routing interception capabilities to redirect those requests to the 
            <code>HttpClient</code> created by <code>TestServer.CreateClient()</code>. This is accomplished using 
            <code>page.RouteAsync()</code> to intercept matching URL patterns and fulfill them with responses from the in-memory 
            server, effectively bridging the gap between the browser's network requests and your in-memory application instance.
        </p>
        <p>
            The following example demonstrates how to set up routing interception. First, create an <code>HttpClient</code> from 
            your test server, then configure Playwright to intercept requests for a specific URL pattern and route them through 
            a handler method:
        </p>
        <code>
            var inMemoryHttpClient = myHttpServer.CreateClient();
            await page.RouteAsync(
                pageUrl,
                route => MyRouteHandlerAsync(inMemoryHttpClient, route))
                .ConfigureAwait(false);
        </code>
        <p>
            The handler method receives each intercepted route from Playwright and processes it by forwarding the request to the 
            in-memory <code>HttpClient</code>. The response from the test server is then converted into a format Playwright can 
            use to fulfill the browser's original request, including status code, body content, and content type headers:
        </p>
        <code>
            private static async Task MyRouteHandlerAsync(HttpClient httpClient, IRoute route)
            {
                using (var request = GetRequestFromRoute(route))
                {
                    var response = await httpClient.SendAsync(request)
                        .ConfigureAwait(false);
                    var routeFulfillOptions = new RouteFulfillOptions
                    {
                        Status = (int)response.StatusCode,
                        Body = await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync().ConfigureAwait(false),
                    };

                    if (response.Content.Headers.ContentType != null)
                    {
                        routeFulfillOptions.ContentType = response.Content.Headers.ContentType.ToString();
                    }

                    await route.FulfillAsync(routeFulfillOptions)
                        .ConfigureAwait(false);
                }
            }
        </code>
        <p>
            This combination enables you to start from your application's home page, extract all internal links from the rendered 
            DOM, follow each link systematically, and verify that every page returns a successful HTTP status code and renders 
            without errors. The crawler can maintain a queue of discovered URLs, track visited pages to avoid infinite loops, 
            and generate comprehensive reports of any issues found during the crawl process.
        </p>

        <h2>Aims and Objectives of Web Crawling</h2>
        <p>
            A comprehensive web crawler for integration testing should capture and verify multiple aspects of your application's 
            behavior. The primary objectives include:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>HTTP Status Code Validation:</strong> Ensure every page returns the expected HTTP status code, typically 
                200 OK for successful pages. Track pages that return 404 Not Found, 500 Internal Server Error, or other error codes.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Console Message Monitoring:</strong> Capture browser console messages (logs, warnings, errors) generated 
                during page navigation. This helps identify JavaScript errors, deprecation warnings, or unexpected client-side 
                behavior that may not cause visible failures but indicates underlying issues. Particular attention should be paid to:
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Content Security Policy (CSP) Violations:</strong> Messages indicating blocked resources due to CSP 
                        rules, which can prevent scripts, styles, or other resources from loading even though they appear in the HTML.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Mixed Content Warnings:</strong> Alerts when HTTPS pages attempt to load HTTP resources, which browsers 
                        may block for security reasons.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) Errors:</strong> Messages indicating failed cross-origin requests 
                        that may prevent API calls or resource loading from different domains.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Deprecation Warnings:</strong> Browser notifications about deprecated APIs or features that may break 
                        in future browser versions.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Page Error Detection:</strong> Track page-level errors such as unhandled exceptions in JavaScript, 
                rendering failures, or timeout issues that could indicate problems with page initialization or resource loading.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Request Failure Tracking:</strong> Monitor failed HTTP requests for resources like images, stylesheets, 
                scripts, or API calls. Failed requests can indicate broken references, missing files, or CORS configuration issues.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Link Discovery and Coverage:</strong> Systematically extract and follow all internal links to ensure 
                complete site coverage. Track which pages have been visited and how many times each URL is referenced, helping 
                identify orphaned pages or broken navigation paths.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Same-Domain Enforcement:</strong> Respect domain boundaries by only following internal links, preventing 
                the crawler from following external links that could lead to infinite crawling or testing third-party sites.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>CSS Validation and Analysis:</strong> Analyze the CSS usage on each page to identify potential styling issues:
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Undefined CSS Classes:</strong> Detect CSS classes that are used in the DOM (applied to HTML elements) 
                        but are not defined in any loaded stylesheet. This can indicate missing CSS files, broken build pipelines, 
                        or references to classes that were removed from stylesheets but remain in the HTML.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Unused CSS Classes:</strong> Identify CSS classes that are defined in stylesheets but never actually 
                        used in the DOM, helping to detect dead code and opportunities for stylesheet optimization.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Cross-Origin Stylesheet Access:</strong> Track when stylesheets cannot be analyzed due to CORS 
                        restrictions, which may hide potential issues in externally hosted CSS files.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Accessibility Validation:</strong> Verify that pages meet basic accessibility standards to ensure they are 
                usable by people with disabilities and compliant with regulations like WCAG (Web Content Accessibility Guidelines):
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Image Alt Attribute Validation:</strong> Check that all <code>&lt;img&gt;</code> elements have 
                        meaningful alternative text. This includes verifying that alt attributes are not empty or whitespace-only, 
                        and optionally validating that alt text follows best practices such as ending with proper punctuation 
                        (typically a period) to ensure screen readers pause appropriately between elements.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Semantic HTML Usage:</strong> Identify pages that may lack proper semantic structure, such as missing 
                        heading hierarchies, landmark regions, or ARIA labels that assist screen readers in navigating content.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <strong>Keyboard Navigation:</strong> Detect interactive elements that may not be keyboard-accessible, 
                        ensuring users who cannot use a mouse can still navigate and interact with the application.
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            By capturing this comprehensive set of metrics, you can build a detailed report of your application's health, 
            identifying not just obvious failures but also subtle issues that may impact user experience or indicate technical debt.
        </p>

        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p>
            Implementing a web crawler as part of your integration testing strategy provides comprehensive coverage that goes far 
            beyond traditional endpoint testing. By combining ASP.NET Core's <code>WebApplicationFactory</code> with Playwright.NET, 
            you create a powerful testing environment that runs entirely in-memory, requiring no external infrastructure while still 
            exercising your application through a real browser engine.
        </p>
        <p>
            The systematic crawling approach automatically discovers and validates every page in your application, capturing a rich 
            set of metrics including HTTP status codes, console messages, page errors, request failures, CSS validation, and 
            accessibility compliance. This comprehensive validation catches issues that might otherwise slip through to production, 
            from broken links and missing resources to subtle problems like Content Security Policy violations, undefined CSS classes, 
            or incomplete alt text on images.
        </p>
        <p>
            Most importantly, this approach is fully automated and can run as part of your CI/CD pipeline without requiring external 
            services or complex infrastructure setup. By investing in web crawling tests, you gain confidence that your entire 
            application is healthy, accessible, and ready for deployment, while also building a valuable regression test suite that 
            continuously validates your application's integrity as it evolves.
        </p>

